message.content:
We begin by extracting the required numbers from the provided statements.

1. Operating Cash Flow Ratio:
 • Definition: Operating CF / Current Liabilities.
 • From the cash flow statement, Net CF from Operating Activities = 1,598,438.00.
 • From the balance sheet, Total Current Liabilities = 2,110,671.05.
 • Therefore: 1,598,438.00 ÷ 2,110,671.05 ≈ 0.757 and we round to 0.76.

2. Cash Flow to Debt Ratio:
 • Definition (using available data): Operating CF / Debt. Here, total debt is considered as the current liabilities.
 • Using the same numbers above: 1,598,438.00 ÷ 2,110,671.05 ≈ 0.757 which rounds to 0.76.

3. Inventory Turnover Ratio:
 • Definition: Cost of Goods Sold ÷ Average Inventory.
 • COGS from the income statement = 3,175,000.00.
 • Inventory at beginning is 0 and at end is 295,000.00 so Average Inventory = (0 + 295,000.00) / 2 = 147,500.00.
 • Therefore: 3,175,000.00 ÷ 147,500.00 ≈ 21.53.

4. Debt to Equity Ratio:
 • Definition: Total Liabilities ÷ Total Owner’s Equity.
 • Total Liabilities (only current liabilities provided) = 2,110,671.05.
 • Total Owner’s Equity from the balance sheet = 14,103,190.60.
 • Thus: 2,110,671.05 ÷ 14,103,190.60 ≈ 0.1497, or 0.15 when rounded.

5. Quick Ratio:
 • Definition: (Total Current Assets – Inventory) ÷ Current Liabilities.
 • Total Current Assets = 10,906,753.86.
 • Inventory = 295,000.00.
 • So, Quick Assets = 10,906,753.86 – 295,000.00 = 10,611,753.86.
 • Then: 10,611,753.86 ÷ 2,110,671.05 ≈ 5.028, which rounds to 5.03.

6. Current Ratio:
 • Definition: Total Current Assets ÷ Current Liabilities.
 • Thus: 10,906,753.86 ÷ 2,110,671.05 ≈ 5.17.
